04493nam a22004935i 9780804768306DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047683067 a10.1515/97808047683062doi  a(DE-B1597)581885  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aLB2351.2b.D68 2007 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a378.1/6109731 aDouglass, John Aubrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Conditions for Admission :bAccess, Equity, and the Social Contract of Public Universities /cJohn Aubrey Douglass. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b15 tables, 13 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tPreface -- tPart I Building a Public University and Creating the Social Contract -- t1. The Public University Movement and California -- t2. Building a Higher Education System and Broadening Access -- t3. Inclusion, Exclusion, and the Issue of Race -- tPart II The Managerial University and the Post–World War II Era -- t4. The Master Plan, the SAT, and Managing Demand -- t5. Countervailing Forces: Standardized Testing and Affirmative Action -- t6. For Every Action a Reaction: Race, Bakke, and the Social Contract Revisited -- tPart III Modern Battles over Equity, Affirmative Action, and Testing -- t7. California’s Affirmative-Action Fight -- t8. The First Aftermath: Outreach and Comprehensive Review -- t9. The Second Aftermath: President Atkinson Versus the SAT -- tPart IV Whither the Social Contract? The Postmodern World and the Primacy of Higher Education -- t10. Perils and Opportunities: Autonomy, Merit, and Privatization -- t11. The Waning of America’s Higher Education Advantage -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe social contract of public universities—the progressive idea that any citizen who meets specified academic conditions can gain entry to their state university—has profoundly shaped American society. This book offers the first comprehensive examination of admission policies and practices at public universities. Using the University of California, the nation's largest public research university and among its most selective, as an illuminating case study, it explores historical and contemporary debates over affirmative action, gender, class, standardized testing, and the growing influences of privatization and globalization, and indeed the very purpose and future of these important public institutions. The United States has been the world leader in developing mass higher education, using its pioneering network of public universities to promote socioeconomic mobility and national economic competitiveness. But the author warns that access and graduation rates have stagnated and may even be declining, particularly among younger students. Other countries, including key members of the European Union, along with China, India, and other developing nations, are aggressively reshaping and expanding their higher education systems. The “American advantage” of a high-quality and high-access higher education system is waning. The closing chapters explore why this is the case and the consequences within an increasingly competitive global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aPublic universities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdmission. 4aEducation. 4aSociology -- Education and Society. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476830640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768306423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768306/original  aGBV-deGruyter-a